Kaveel Singh, News24Mxolisi Kaunda (Amanda Khoza, News24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Durban &ndash; The KwaZulu-Natal MEC for Transport, Community Safety and Liaison, Mxolisi Kaunda, on Sunday called on the taxi industry to end violence. &ldquo;Violence will never solve problems, it only begets more violence.&nbsp; We call for an end to violence in the taxi industry, because our priority is to help it grow to greater heights.&rdquo; Kaunda added that there must be respect for the rule of law. The newly-appointed MEC was speaking in a meeting with the South African National Taxi Council (Santaco). Kaunda said he would work together with the taxi industry to improve relations.&ldquo;This government has prioritised economic transformation therefore this industry is important, because it has buying power. You must look at the bigger picture and make a meaningful impact, and ensure that African people benefit from the economic growth of the country,&rdquo; said Kaunda.Kaunda added that industry players should prioritise peaceful negotiations.&nbsp;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.